\Please translate the following:

material interno, raramente visto por el programador:\\ internal stuff, rarely seen by the programmer:

Un número-x es un número. \An x-number is a number.
Un número-y es un número. \A y-number is a number.
Un par tiene un número-x y un número-y. \A pair has an x-number and a y-number.

Una distancia son algunos twips. \A distance is some twips.

\\ I had to put dashes in 'x number" and "y number" (here) and in "x coord" and "y coord" (below) because "y",
\\ by itself, in Spanish means "and".

\cursores \\ cursors

El cursor flecha es un cursor. \The arrow cursor is a cursor. Alt. name for simplicity or problems with inverted order of words: La flecha cursor
El cursor mano es un cursor. \The hand cursor is a cursor. Alt. name: La mano cursor
El cursor rayo-i \The i-beam cursor is a cursor.

Para esconder el cursor: \To hide a cursor:
Para mostrar el cursor: \To show a cursor:

colores \\ colors

\To pick a color between another color and a third color:

\puntos \\ spots

\Is "foco" the right word for "spot"? A spot is like a mathematical point, only it has width and height.
\A spot is about 1/15 of a pixel, but in practice usually refers to a particular pixel.
\Google translates it as "lugar" which means "place" or "space".
It could be used "punto" for spot, or even "pixel" for pixel. But I said "foco" for the mouse spot as "foco del ratón".
I think that foco, punto and pixel could be defined all as spot and use any of them when convenient.

Una coordenada-x es una coordenada. \An x-coord is a coord. 
Una coordenada-y es una coordenada. \A y-coord is a coord.

\ "coord" is short for "coordinate" It's an ugly word either way.
We love whole words. We can't pronounce such ugly abreviations as English could, we love vowels not consonant clusters everywhere.
Every foreign word that start with an S followed by consonant we say "ES..." and never "SS...".
You could also hear how our Brazilians cousins love vowels, they can't pronounce even "New York", "ping pong", they say "New Yorkie", "pinggie ponggie".

Un punto es un par con una coordenada-x y una coordenada-y y una (coordenada) izquierda en la coordenada-x y una (coordenada) superior en la coordenada-y.
\A spot is a pair with an x-coord and a y-coord and a left at the x-coord and a top at the y-coord.
What is a left? What is a top?... Ah! a coord! (I read the definition below)

Para hacer un punto con una coordenada-x y una coordenada-y: \To make a spot with an x-coord and a y-coord:
Para elegir un punto a cierta distancia de otro punto: \To pick a spot within a distance of another spot:
\"a cierta"/"a una" more natural than "dentro (de) una" or "en una" both lit. translat. of "within a"
\this "a ..." could cause problems?

Para dibujar un punto con un color: \To draw a spot with a color:

\cuadros/cajas/rectángulos\\ boxes
I can't remember first translation we used for box; cajas and cuadros are fine.
Beware: 
a/the box: una/la caja     |    un/el cuadro
the boxes:  las cajas         |    los cuadros

Una caja tiene \A box has
una coordenada izquierda, una coordenada superior, una coordenada derecha, una coordenada inferior,\A left coord, a top coord, a right coord, a bottom coord,
un punto superior-izquierda en la izquierda, y un punto inferior-derecha en la derecha. \A left-top spot at the left, and a right-bottom spot at the right.

Para hacer una caja algunos twips por algunos otros twips: \To make a box some twips by some other twips:

Para dibujar una caja con un color (de) borde y un color (de) relleno: \To draw a box with a border color and a fill color:
\this "de" could cause problems? It is not natural without the "de"

Para elegir un punto doquiera dentro de una caja: \To pick a spot anywhere in a box:

\elipses \\ ellipses

Una elipse tiene una caja. \An ellipse has a box.

Para dibujar una elipse con un color (de) borde y un color (de) relleno: \To draw an ellipse with a border color and a fill color:

\cadenas, subcadenas, y punteros \\ strings, substrings, and riders
Rider is "jinete" the one who rides a horse only, never a bike. It is not a word for this technical use in Spanish, not natural.
I would say that a rider is a pointer, in Spanish "puntero". What do you think?

Un byte es un puntero a un byte. \A byte pointer is a pointer to a byte.

We say byte from English; some books and the Spaniards say "octeto" like the French, that don't want to use any English word.

Una cadena tiene un puntero al primer byte y un puntero al último byte. \A string has a first byte pointer and a last byte pointer.
Una cadena tiene un puntero al inicio y un puntero al fin.
Una cadena tiene un puntero inicial y un puntero final.

Para poner una cadena en otra cadena: \To put a string into another string:

Una subcadena es una cadena. \A substring is a string.

Un puntero tiene \A rider has
Una subcadena original, \An original substring,
Una subcadena fuente y \A source substring and 
Un subcadena clave. \A token substring.

We don't have a good translation for token, I'm choosing "clave" similar to key or password in Spanish.

\miscelánea \\ miscellaneous

\In English we consider "from/given/with/using" as interchangeable. What are the Spanish equivalents?
I need to read the English interchangeable cases to judge this.
First approach lit.:
desde/dado/con/usando

from: de/desde

\Is there a shorter word for "interrumpir"? Google suggests, "rompo".
"Rompo" is lit. for I destroy (a thing)
Break: the intention is to jump to the end of the loop and start again, isn't it? We could say "salte" lit. for jump, we could understand it as "jump the rest".
Exit: it could be "sale" lit. for "it comes out"; right now I guess is "salida", exit as a noun not a verb.

